    <main>
      <h2>Friends of Bushland 261</h2>
      
      <div class="content">
	<p>
	  Its name sounds like the zone<br>
On a map, a lonely hill<br>
That thousands would die for<br>
	  In Korea
	</p>

	<p>
A living thing become a number<br>
To be annihilated as the waves<br>
Of bulldozers come rolling in,<br>
Blades at the ready.
	</p>

	<p>
Less than a square kilometre,<br>
Criss-crossed by sandy paths<br>
Littered between the grass trees<br>
And tuarts, remnants of a bigger age
	</p>

	<p>
The old swamp was filled in<br>
Sixty years ago, but you can still see<br>
Where the puddles pool towards the middle<br>
When the rain comes,
	</p>

	<p>
Where it would have drained<br>
Toward the Canning River.
	</p>

	<p>
The cries of five hundred cockatoos when they choose<br>
To take up residence, send a shiver<br>
Through the spines of the biggest trees,<br>
The basis of life itself.
	</p>

	<p>
And you can still see the little quendas<br>
Scurry about at night, no longer called<br>
Native rats by their neighbours.
	</p>

	<p>
	  The bike barriers at both ends<br>
	  Don’t stop the little kids,<br>
Confused old grannies leave tidy piles of dog shit<br>
	  In bright yellow plastic bags
	</p>

	<p>
Here the line will hold.<br>
Here in the shade of the old gum trees,<br>
A rag-tag band of dog walkers, bird watchers, and old hippies<br>
A few uni students, wearing the shirts of the greens
	</p>

	<p>
To protect this, last stand<br>
Of the once all encompassing bushland;<br>
Defiant refusal to move on, the local against machine,<br>
Demanding that the suburbs too
	</p>

	<p>
Can keep one tiny patch of life,<br>
A record of the ecocide that was done;<br>
A line stands ready to fight<br>
For a space off the grid,
	</p>
	
	<p>
	  For Bushland 261.
	</p>
      </div>
      
